'''Seko Mohamed Fofana''' (born 7 May 1995) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Primeira Liga]] club [[FC Porto|Porto]], on loan from [[Ligue 1]] club [[Stade Rennais FC|Rennes]]. Born in France, he plays for the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast national team]].

==Club career==
===Manchester City===
Born in [[Paris]], France, Fofana began his youth career at [[Paris FC]] when he was nine and stayed there for six years before joining [[FC Lorient|Lorient]].<ref name="FofanaFM">{{cite news|title=Info FM : à la découverte de Seko Fofana, la pépite française de Man City|url=http://www.footmercato.net/autre-championnat/info-fm-a-la-decouverte-de-seko-fofana-la-pepite-francaise-de-man-city_127480|publisher=Foot Mercato|date=6 April 2014|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=23 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923224407/http://www.footmercato.net/autre-championnat/info-fm-a-la-decouverte-de-seko-fofana-la-pepite-francaise-de-man-city_127480|url-status=live}}</ref> After two years at Lorient,<ref name="FofanaFM"/> he moved to [[England]] when he joined [[Premier League]] side [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2013 and was immediately sent to the [[Manchester City F.C. Reserves and Academy|development squad]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/Teams/EDS/Midfielders/Seko-Fofana|title=Player Profile - Seko Fofana|publisher=Manchester City F.C.|accessdate=20 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140803033213/http://www.mcfc.co.uk/Teams/EDS/Midfielders/Seko-Fofana|archivedate=3 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Fofana began to be a regular in the under-18s in the 2013–14 season, making 20 appearances and scoring 5 goals in the league and playing 7 times scoring twice in [[Manchester City F.C. Reserves and Academy|the club]]'s [[2013–14 UEFA Youth League|UEFA Youth League]] campaign against [[PFC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Match Report: Manchester City U19s 1 CSKA U19s 2|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/manchester-city-u19s-1-cska-6274261|publisher=Manchester Evening News|date=5 November 2013|accessdate=24 September 2016|archive-date=27 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927072525/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/manchester-city-u19s-1-cska-6274261|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[S.L. Benfica Juniors|Benfica Juniors]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Manchester City U19 1 Benfica Juniors 2: Young Blues crash out of UEFA Youth League|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/city-1-benfica-2-young-6848627|publisher=Manchester Evening news|date=18 March 2014|accessdate=24 September 2016|archive-date=27 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927081650/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/city-1-benfica-2-young-6848627|url-status=live}}</ref> During [[Manchester City F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester City]]'s U21 friendly match against [[HNK Rijeka]], he was racially abused by one of the opposition players just before half-time. As a result, players from Manchester City's U21 squad walked off the pitch, prompting the match to be cancelled.<ref>{{cite news|title=Racism Claim Halts Manchester City Friendly|url=http://news.sky.com/story/racism-claim-halts-manchester-city-friendly-10395742|publisher=Sky News|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=24 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924113351/http://news.sky.com/story/racism-claim-halts-manchester-city-friendly-10395742|url-status=live}}</ref> After the match, Manager [[Patrick Vieira]] praised the action of the players to walk out.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vieira praised for EDS walkoff|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/manchester-city-eds-racism-claims-7487674|publisher=Manchester Evening News|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=24 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924173353/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/manchester-city-eds-racism-claims-7487674|url-status=live}}</ref>

====Fulham (loan)====
On 27 November 2014, Fofana signed for [[Football Championship|Championship]] side [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on loan until 31 January 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2014/november/27/fofana-joins-on-loan|title=Fofana Joins On Loan|publisher=Fulham FC|date=27 November 2014|accessdate=30 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045904/http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2014/november/27/fofana-joins-on-loan|archivedate=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He made his Fulham debut two days later, where he came on as a substitute for [[Emerson Hyndman]] in the 63rd minute, in a 2–1 win over [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sky Bet Championship: Fulham come from behind to beat Brighton 2-1|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/brighton-vs-fulham/report/313987|publisher=Sky Sports|date=30 November 2014|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=24 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924100441/http://www.skysports.com/football/brighton-vs-fulham/report/313987|url-status=live}}</ref> His form and performance convinced Fulham to extend the loan spell until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Seko Fofana: Fulham extend Manchester City man's loan spell|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30888095|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 January 2015|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=8 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210108102150/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30888095|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 21 March 2015 to secure a 2–0 win away to [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31882508|title=Huddersfield Town 0-2 Fulham|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 March 2015|access-date=9 July 2015|archive-date=3 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150603224917/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31882508|url-status=live}}</ref> Having established himself under the management of [[Kit Symons]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2015/february/03/pro-seko-maturing-with-age|title=Pro Seko In Sparkling Form|publisher=Fulham F.C.|date=3 February 2015|accessdate=20 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923232406/http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2015/february/03/pro-seko-maturing-with-age|archivedate=23 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Fofana went on to make 25 appearances scoring once before returning to his parent club.

====Bastia (loan)====
[[File:Seko Fofana (SC Bastia).JPG|upright|thumb|Fofana with Bastia in 2016]]
After making two appearances for City during their pre-season tour in Australia (playing the second half of a 2–0 win over [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Adelaide United 0-2 Man City: Brandon Barker and Bruno Zuculini on target|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11679/9913616/adelaide-united-0-2-man-city-brandon-barker-and-bruno-zuculini-on-target|publisher=Sky Sports|date=15 July 2015|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=24 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924101053/http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11679/9913616/adelaide-united-0-2-man-city-brandon-barker-and-bruno-zuculini-on-target|url-status=live}}</ref> and coming on as a late [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in Manchester City's 1–0 win over [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]]),<ref>{{cite news|title=Melbourne City 0-1 Manchester City: Samir Nasri scores only goal|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11679/9916783/melbourne-city-0-1-manchester-city-samir-nasri-scores-only-goal|publisher=Sky Sports|date=18 July 2015|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=24 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924100702/http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11679/9916783/melbourne-city-0-1-manchester-city-samir-nasri-scores-only-goal|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Premier League]] club agreed to send Fofana out on loan again to gain further experience. The Frenchman subsequently returned to his native France, to join [[SC Bastia|Bastia]] on a season-long loan on 29 July 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/News/EDS-news/2015/July/Seko-Fofana-joins-Bastia-on-loan/1438186732|title=Seko Fofana joins Bastia on loan|publisher=Manchester City F.C.|date=29 July 2015|accessdate=20 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802015541/http://www.mcfc.co.uk/News/EDS-news/2015/July/Seko-Fofana-joins-Bastia-on-loan/1438186732|archivedate=2 August 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> He made his [[Ligue 1]] debut in the opening game of the season 10 days later, on 8 August 2015, playing the full 90 minutes in a 2−1 win at home to [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bastia-Rennes (2-1), Bastia renverse Rennes|url=http://www.goal.com/fr/match/bastia-vs-rennes/2045818/report|publisher=Goal.com|language=French|date=8 August 2015|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=13 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013012839/http://www.goal.com/fr/match/bastia-vs-rennes/2045818/report|url-status=live}}</ref> He then scored his first goal on 12 December 2015, in a 1–1 draw against [[Troyes AC|Troyes]],<ref>{{cite news|title=TOUJOURS PAS DE VICTOIRE POUR TROYES|url=http://www.football365.fr/toujours-pas-de-victoire-pour-troyes-2128537.html|publisher=Football 365|language=French|date=12 December 2015|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=24 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924123640/http://www.football365.fr/toujours-pas-de-victoire-pour-troyes-2128537.html|url-status=live}}</ref> followed up by assisting in the next game on 19 December 2015, in a 2–0 win over [[Stade de Reims|Reims]].<ref>{{cite news|title=BASTIA PASSERA LES FÊTES AU CHAUD|url=http://www.football365.fr/bastia-passera-les-fetes-au-chaud-2128661.html|publisher=Football 365|language=French|date=19 December 2015|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=24 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924110757/http://www.football365.fr/bastia-passera-les-fetes-au-chaud-2128661.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In a 1–0 win over [[Montpellier HSC|Montpellier]] on 16 January 2016, Fofana received a straight red card in the 65th minutes.<ref>{{cite news|title=BASTIA FAIT REPLONGER MONTPELLIER|url=http://www.football365.fr/bastia-fait-replonger-montpellier-2128835.html|publisher=Football 365|language=French|date=16 January 2016|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=24 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924093004/http://www.football365.fr/bastia-fait-replonger-montpellier-2128835.html|url-status=live}}</ref> After the match, he was given a four match ban<ref>{{cite news|title=Commission de discipline : le Bastiais Seko Fofana prend 4 matches|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Commission-de-discipline-le-bastiais-seko-fofana-prend-4-matches/626850|publisher=L'Equipe|language=French|date=21 January 2016|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=24 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924104825/http://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Commission-de-discipline-le-bastiais-seko-fofana-prend-4-matches/626850|url-status=live}}</ref> and Fofana, himself, apologised for his action.<ref>{{cite news|title=Seko Fofana s'est excusé auprès de Jonas Martin pour son coup de boule|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Seko-fofana-s-est-excuse-aupres-de-jonas-martin-pour-son-coup-de-boule/625399|publisher=L'Equipe|language=French|date=17 January 2016|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=24 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924113715/http://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Seko-fofana-s-est-excuse-aupres-de-jonas-martin-pour-son-coup-de-boule/625399|url-status=live}}</ref> In total, he made 32 appearances and scoring once for Bastia.

===Udinese===
After three years at Manchester City, Fofana joined [[Serie A]] side [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]], signing a five-year deal for worth £2.5 million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Udinese sign Manchester City midfielder Seko Fofana - report|url=http://www.espnfc.co.uk/story/2900563/udinese-sign-manchester-city-midfielder-seko-fofana-report|publisher=ESPN|date=23 June 2016|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=23 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923223303/http://www.espnfc.co.uk/story/2900563/udinese-sign-manchester-city-midfielder-seko-fofana-report|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, the move included a possible €2 million bonus and Bastia receiving 15% of the total compensation, up to €700K.<ref>{{cite news|title=Transfert Seko Fofana quitte Manchester City pour l'Udinese|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Seko-fofana-quitte-manchester-city-pour-l-udinese/697953|publisher=L'Equipe|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=23 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923223552/http://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Seko-fofana-quitte-manchester-city-pour-l-udinese/697953|url-status=live}}</ref> Fofana made his Udinese debut in the opening game of the season playing 79 minutes before being substituted, in a 4–0 loss against [[A.S. Roma|Roma]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Roma-Udinese 4-0: super Perotti, i giallorossi calano subito il poker|url=http://www.repubblica.it/sport/calcio/serie-a/2016/08/20/news/roma-udinese_4-0_super_perotti_i_giallorossi_calano_subito_il_poker-146335593/|publisher=Repubblica.it|language=Italian|date=20 August 2016|accessdate=24 September 2016|archive-date=27 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527122345/http://www.repubblica.it/sport/calcio/serie-a/2016/08/20/news/roma-udinese_4-0_super_perotti_i_giallorossi_calano_subito_il_poker-146335593/|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Lens ===
On 18 August 2020, Fofana signed a four-year contract with [[Ligue 1]] club [[RC Lens|Lens]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=18 August 2020|title=Seko Fofana: Lens sign former Manchester City midfielder from Udinese|url=https://www.goal.com/en-ng/news/seko-fofana-lens-sign-former-manchester-city-midfielder-from/1c7ajckt6qa3n1aoa32ljhk4oh|access-date=2 October 2020|website=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|archive-date=1 January 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230101140235/https://www.goal.com/en-ng/news/seko-fofana-lens-sign-former-manchester-city-midfielder-from/1c7ajckt6qa3n1aoa32ljhk4oh|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored his first goal on 21 February 2021 against [[Dijon FCO|Dijon]]. After a string of good performances, he was awarded the [[Ligue 1 Player of the Month]] for September 2021. In May 2022, Fofana won the [[Prix Marc-Vivien Foé]] as the best African player in France's top flight for the [[2021–22 Ligue 1|2021–22 campaign]], following a season in which he scored eight goals in 37 appearances.<ref name="PMVF">{{cite web |date=16 May 2022 |title=Seko Fofana: Lens and Ivory Coast player wins Marc-Vivien Foe award |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/61465028 |accessdate=16 May 2022 |website=BBC |archive-date=16 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220516160202/https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/61465028 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 31 August 2022, he signed a contract extension with the club until 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-09-01 |title=Seko Fofana signs emotional new contract at Lens - in front of full stadium |url=https://www.sporf.com/seko-fofana-signs-new-deal-at-lens-in-front-of-full-stadium/ |access-date=2023-02-24 |website=SPORF |language=en-US |archive-date=24 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230224182045/https://www.sporf.com/seko-fofana-signs-new-deal-at-lens-in-front-of-full-stadium/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Al-Nassr ===
On 18 July 2023, Fofana joined [[Saudi Pro League]] club [[Al Nassr FC|Al Nassr]] on a three-year deal, reportedly for a fee of €25 million.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rai |first1=Guillermo |last2=Cortegana |first2=Mario |title=Lens captain Seko Fofana completes €25m transfer to Saudi Pro League side Al Nassr |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4699440/2023/07/18/seko-fofana-al-nassr-transfer-saudi/ |website=The Athletic |access-date=18 July 2023 |date=18 July 2023 |archive-date=18 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230718151030/https://theathletic.com/4699440/2023/07/18/seko-fofana-al-nassr-transfer-saudi/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Al-Ettifaq (loan) ====
On 30 January 2024, Fofana joined fellow Saudi Arabian side [[Al-Ettifaq FC|Al-Ettifaq]] on a six-month loan.<ref>{{cite web |title=لاعب النصر العاجي فوفانا يدعم وسط الاتفاق بنظام الإعارة |url=https://ettifaq.com/news/30-01-2024-3/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/lists/seko-fofana-leaves-cristiano-ronaldo-al-nassr-for-al-ettifaq-on-loan-steven-gerrard/bltcc7172b7342f1770|title=Steven Gerrard has his Jordan Henderson replacement! Seko Fofana leaves Cristiano Ronaldo's Al-Nassr for Al-Ettifaq on loan|website=Goal|date=30 January 2024|accessdate=31 January 2024}}</ref> On 17 August 2024, Fofana re-joined Al-Ettifaq on a one-year loan.<ref>{{cite web |title=رسميّا.. الاتفاق يمدد إعارة فوفانا |url=https://arriyadiyah.com/847125}}</ref>

=== Rennes ===
On 1 January 2025, Fofana returned to Ligue 1 and joined [[Stade Rennais FC|Rennes]] on a four-and-a-half years contract.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-08-30 |title=Seko Fofana joins Stade Rennais {{!}} Stade Rennais F.C. |url=https://www.staderennais.com/en/news/degemer-mat-seko |access-date=2025-01-01 |publisher=[[Stade Rennais F.C.]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-01-01 |title=Seko Fofana is back! |url=https://ligue1.com/articles/l1_article_1575-seko-fofana-is-back |access-date=2025-01-05 |publisher=Ligue 1 |language=en}}</ref> The transfer was completed for a fee of €20 million, establishing him as the most expensive sale in the history of the Saudi Pro League.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Millar |first=Colin |title=Seko Fofana leaves Al Nassr to join Rennes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6031456/2025/01/01/seko-fofana-al-nassr-transfer-rennes/ |access-date=2025-01-01 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 2025 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

==== Porto (loan) ====
On 2 February 2026, Fofana was sent on loan to [[Primeira Liga]] club [[FC Porto|Porto]] until the end of the [[2025–26 FC Porto season|2025–26 season]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Seko Fofana é Dragão |url=https://www.fcporto.pt/pt/noticias/20260202-pt-seko-fofana-e-dragao |publisher=[[FC Porto]] |date=2 February 2026 |language=pt}}</ref>

==International career==
Fofana was eligible to play for [[France national football team|France]] and [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]], as his parents come from there.<ref>{{cite news|title=Seko Fofana (Bastia) dragué par la Côte d'Ivoire|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Seko-fofana-bastia-drague-par-la-cote-d-ivoire/632455|publisher=L'Equipe|language=French|date=7 February 2016|accessdate=23 September 2016|archive-date=24 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224221916/http://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Seko-fofana-bastia-drague-par-la-cote-d-ivoire/632455/|url-status=live}}</ref> Fofana previously represented [[France national under-16 football team|France U16]], [[France national under-17 football team|France U17]], [[France national under-18 football team|France U18]] and [[France national under-19 football team|France U19]]. On 3 April 2017, Fofana chose to represent the Ivory Coast, the country of his parents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Cote-d-ivoire-maxwell-cornet-et-seko-fofana-ont-choisi-de-jouer-pour-les-elephants/790457|title=Côte d'Ivoire : Maxwel Cornet et Seko Fofana ont choisi de jouer pour les Eléphants|last=Rédaction|publisher=|access-date=4 December 2017|archive-date=20 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191220075146/https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Cote-d-ivoire-maxwell-cornet-et-seko-fofana-ont-choisi-de-jouer-pour-les-elephants/790457|url-status=live}}</ref>

Fofana made his debut for Ivory Coast in a 2–0 [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification]] loss to [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] on 11 November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=276412/match=300367120/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160819073112/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=276412/match=300367120/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 August 2016|title=2018 FIFA World Cup Russia - Matches - Ivory Coast-Morocco |last=FIFA.com|website=FIFA.com}}</ref>

In December 2023, Fofana was named in the Ivory Coast's squad for the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/federationivoiriennedefootball/posts/pfbid02GVkTYXjhv2yBQizHRNxngTGoMrFLXgcUg3kQeXgEk3gZ158w6cxqRFjDBXCCU3ihl|title=LA LISTE|publisher=[[Ivorian Football Federation]]|date=28 December 2023|access-date=16 January 2024|language=pt|via=[[Facebook]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.7info.ci/cote-divoire-voici-les-27-elephants-de-gasset-zaha-et-des-tenors-font-leurs-adieux-a-la-can-2023/|title=Côte d'Ivoire: voici les 27 Eléphants de Gasset, Zaha et des ténors font leurs adieux à la CAN 2023|publisher=[[7info]]|first=Tristan|last=Sahi|date=28 December 2023|access-date=16 January 2024|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cafonline.com/media/ow2obxrw/c%C3%B4te-divoire.pdf|title=CÔTE D'IVOIRE|publisher=Confederation of African Football|date=5 January 2024}}</ref> He scored the opening goal of the tournament four minutes into Ivory Coast's 2–0 win over [[Guinea-Bissau national football team|Guinea-Bissau]] on 13 January 2024.<ref name=AFCONgoal>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/sports/2024/1/14/afcon-ivory-coast-vs-guinea-bissau-africa-cup-of-nations-2023|title=Ivory Coast open AFCON 2023 with 2-0 win over Guinea-Bissau|date=14 January 2024|access-date=16 January 2024|website=Al Jazeera}}</ref>

Fofana was included in the list of Ivorian players selected by coach [[Emerse Faé]] to participate in the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|date=9 December 2025 |language=fr |title=Nicolas Pépé et Simon Adingra absents, Wilfried Zaha de retour : la liste de la Côte d'Ivoire pour la CAN |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Nicolas-pepe-et-simon-adingra-absents-wilfried-zaha-de-retour-la-liste-de-la-cote-d-ivoire-pour-la-can/1615689 |website=www.lequipe.fr}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref><ref>{{cite web|date=9 December 2025 |language=fr |title=CAN 2025: la liste de la Côte d'Ivoire, tenante du titre, avec le retour de Wilfried Zaha |url=https://www.rfi.fr/fr/afrique-foot/20251209-can-2025-la-liste-de-la-c%C3%B4te-d-ivoire-tenante-du-titre-avec-le-retour-de-wilfried-zaha |website=www.rfi.fr}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref>

On May 15, 2026, Fofana was integrated by Ivory Coast coach [[Emerse Faé]] in his list of 26 players in order to participate in the [[2026 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|access-date=2 June 2026 |date=15 May 2026 |language=fr |title=La liste de la Côte d'Ivoire pour la Coupe du Monde 2026 |url=https://www.fifa.com/fr/articles/liste-cote-d-ivoire-coupe-du-monde-2026 |website=[[FIFA]]}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref>

